WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.640
Hi everybody, good afternoon. Thank you for being here, and thank you to Daniel and Liz

00:00:13.640 --> 00:00:19.879
and Andrew. Awesome talks so far, really appreciate that, a lot of good info in there. Welcome

00:00:19.879 --> 00:00:26.280
everybody who's coming in, and thank you for coming to see me. My name is Patrick Tennant,

00:00:26.280 --> 00:00:32.439
and the title of my talk is Serenity Now, Productivity Later. So, I'm going to start

00:00:32.439 --> 00:00:39.919
with a quick story, and I think it's one you're going to recognize. It's early one morning,

00:00:39.919 --> 00:00:46.599
my daughters have just left for school, and so my house is still and quiet. It's about

00:00:46.599 --> 00:00:51.480
7 a.m., so I've just poured my fourth cup of coffee, and I'm ready to rock and roll.

00:00:51.480 --> 00:00:54.919
You know, I'm excited, I'm feeling positive about the day, looking forward to getting

00:00:54.919 --> 00:01:01.639
a lot of stuff done. I go upstairs, and I sit down at my desk, and I open my work email,

00:01:01.639 --> 00:01:08.519
and boom, a flood of messages from my boss. She's got new project ideas, she's got additions

00:01:08.519 --> 00:01:13.160
to existing projects, she's got additions to those additions, right? There's a lot of

00:01:13.160 --> 00:01:19.239
stuff in my inbox this morning, and I start thinking, you know, I had enough to do today

00:01:19.239 --> 00:01:25.400
already. I did not need more on my project stack, and as I start to go through these

00:01:25.400 --> 00:01:32.959
new suggestions, these new ideas, I feel just sort of like this. I'm going to call this

00:01:32.959 --> 00:01:37.720
feeling deflated, but I actually just don't know the word in English that is as accurate

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:41.959
as this for the feeling that I have in that moment, where you just, you're zapped, right?

00:01:41.959 --> 00:01:45.720
You've sort of lost your motivation, your excitement for the day. You're just feeling

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:51.160
like, man, I am overwhelmed, and I almost want to do nothing, just because I have so

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:57.199
much to do. So, I tell you the story, because like I said, I think it's probably recognizable

00:01:57.199 --> 00:02:03.000
to many of you. We all sort of have this moment where we feel overwhelmed and kind of want

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:09.759
to pull in, right? Rather than do more, we want to pull in. That deflated loss of momentum,

00:02:09.759 --> 00:02:15.679
loss of motivation feeling. Now, my talk today is about something we can do about that. Something

00:02:15.759 --> 00:02:20.440
my team has learned that has helped us to address this feeling and the things that lead

00:02:20.440 --> 00:02:25.960
to it. But really, I want to step back first and talk about just that, which is like, why

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:31.039
does this happen? Where is this feeling coming from? Because you might just think, well,

00:02:31.039 --> 00:02:35.559
your boss is the villain, right? She sends you all these new ideas, and she makes you

00:02:35.559 --> 00:02:40.880
feel overwhelmed. That's the problem. You need a new boss. But in my case, at least,

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:44.839
that's really not the problem. I really like my boss, and I really think the fact that

00:02:44.839 --> 00:02:49.600
she has all these good ideas is a good thing, right? It's a good characteristic for a boss

00:02:49.600 --> 00:02:56.720
to have. And so, I'm not going to blame her. And even if in your version of that story,

00:02:56.720 --> 00:03:00.360
whatever the details are in your version of that story, you feel like your boss really

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:04.679
is the problem, what I'm going to suggest to you is that that is not a super helpful

00:03:04.679 --> 00:03:09.279
frame to put on the problem. Maybe you should think about this a little bit differently,

00:03:09.279 --> 00:03:12.919
because if that's your frame, the only real answer is to get a new boss. And sometimes

00:03:12.919 --> 00:03:16.839
that's not a good idea. Sometimes it's not possible. But generally, I think there's a

00:03:16.839 --> 00:03:20.679
more agentic way we can think about this, right? There's a way that kind of puts you

00:03:20.679 --> 00:03:24.720
more in the driver's seat. And that's to think about what is happening inside of you when

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:28.919
that flood of messages comes in, right? Why is it that this flood of messages is giving

00:03:28.919 --> 00:03:36.119
us this deflated feeling where we've lost all of our momentum and motivation in the moment?

00:03:36.119 --> 00:03:39.160
And so, that's what I want to talk about. I want to talk about, like, what is that cycle

00:03:39.160 --> 00:03:43.880
for you and how my team has learned to get out of it, and how I hope you can get out

00:03:43.880 --> 00:03:47.119
of it yourself. So, I'm going to propose that the thing that is happening inside of all

00:03:47.119 --> 00:03:55.080
of us in that moment is FOMO. Our old friend FOMO. A pretty common idea in American society,

00:03:55.080 --> 00:04:00.039
at least. But you might not have thought of this fear of missing out so much in the business

00:04:00.039 --> 00:04:04.080
context before, or in the professional context. But I think it really does apply, right? There's

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:08.839
a way in which this really maps cleanly on to our experience. And that, you know, we're

00:04:08.839 --> 00:04:14.559
afraid of missing out on a promotion or a raise or a bonus, right? We're afraid of missing

00:04:14.559 --> 00:04:19.559
out on an opportunity to make our boss happy or make our team look good, right? So, that

00:04:19.559 --> 00:04:26.320
FOMO that is, you know, applied in the business setting is what's leading us to take on more

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:31.200
than we should, right? To accept that overwhelming stack of projects. To try to roll with that

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:35.079
because we're afraid of missing out on any one of them. And in doing so, we actually

00:04:35.079 --> 00:04:39.160
just lead ourselves to that deflated place, right? So, I'm proposing that FOMO is really

00:04:39.160 --> 00:04:44.480
the problem here. And actually, it's even worse than that because in data science, I

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:53.399
think we have a very specific acute version of this. That would be FOMO abstapa. That

00:04:53.399 --> 00:05:00.959
is the fear of missing out on awesome data science projects. So, this is specific to

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:05.200
us, right? This is our room and this is our version of FOMO. And I think it's one that

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:11.799
we have for some really good reasons, actually. Because in data science, we have this sort

00:05:11.799 --> 00:05:16.359
of unlimited universe of data that we could use, right? Everybody talks about it all the

00:05:16.359 --> 00:05:20.239
time. There's more data that we could possibly lay hands on. And then we have all of these

00:05:20.239 --> 00:05:24.839
awesome tools that we can use to do great things with all of that data. That's really

00:05:24.839 --> 00:05:28.799
what this conference is, right? This conference is about having the amazing tools and the

00:05:28.799 --> 00:05:33.359
great teams that allow us to do great things with this universe of data. That unlimited

00:05:33.359 --> 00:05:40.279
landscape makes FOMO really, really acute because you don't know if that next thing,

00:05:40.279 --> 00:05:45.399
if that next version of this project, that next model, that next run of this iterative

00:05:45.399 --> 00:05:49.760
process is going to get you to that awesome thing, right? The beautifully produced video

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:55.720
we saw this morning before the keynote talks about cleaning rivers or getting us to the

00:05:55.720 --> 00:06:00.920
moon, right? These are big, amazing things. So I don't say this glibly. I mean it genuinely.

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:05.959
There are really, really important projects that we can do. But because of this unlimited

00:06:05.959 --> 00:06:10.600
landscape, we feel like we need to do more. And so that's what I'm talking about today,

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:13.920
is that feeling that we feel like we need to do more and that leads us to take on more

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:19.119
than we can and to feel overwhelmed and to feel deflated. So my suggestion is that we

00:06:19.119 --> 00:06:25.119
actually do less, right? It might feel like we need to do more, but let's do less. And

00:06:25.119 --> 00:06:29.119
this is not a totally novel idea. You've probably come across this in some form or

00:06:29.119 --> 00:06:34.000
fashion before. There's a lot of research backing it up, a pretty robust literature

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:40.399
around this idea. Book chapters, whole books, in fact. And of course, there is a Harvard

00:06:40.399 --> 00:06:44.839
Business Review article on exactly this. Want to be more productive? Try doing less. So

00:06:44.839 --> 00:06:51.000
simple. Thank you, HBR. I'm actually just going to wrap it up with a quote that I really

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:55.359
like that I think sums all of this up pretty well, which is from Shane Parrish, who writes

00:06:55.359 --> 00:07:00.160
the awesome Farnam Street blog. He says, the most powerful productivity tool ever invented

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:07.600
is simply the word no, right? That's nice, right? But it's kind of deceptively simple

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:14.440
and it makes it sound like all you have to do is say no, right? Just say no. It is, of

00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:19.799
course, not actually all that easy. Saying no is hard. We have this FOMO. We don't want

00:07:19.799 --> 00:07:26.000
to say no. And then you add this layer where your boss, or my boss in this case, is sending

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:29.799
all of these ideas. So the person we have to say no to is the boss, right? This is exactly

00:07:29.799 --> 00:07:34.679
the person you don't want to say no to. So the rest of this is my story of how I learned

00:07:34.679 --> 00:07:40.839
to say no to the boss. And that's when we get to the Eisenhower matrix. So the Eisenhower

00:07:40.839 --> 00:07:45.559
matrix is named for former President Dwight Eisenhower. And it's basically a task management

00:07:45.559 --> 00:07:49.119
tool. It's a pretty simple idea. It's been around for a long time, as you can probably

00:07:49.119 --> 00:07:54.959
tell. It's named for Dwight Eisenhower. So we have a task management tool in which we're

00:07:54.959 --> 00:08:00.619
rating our tasks on urgency and importance, right? So each task is getting a rating on

00:08:00.619 --> 00:08:04.119
each of these characteristics. And then we're just laying them out on a grid. Nothing so

00:08:04.119 --> 00:08:10.239
complicated about this. Imagine you have four tasks and they're rated like this. And so

00:08:10.239 --> 00:08:14.640
we would think about each task one by one. And it's going to help guide us to our next

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:20.320
step for that task. Task one here, very urgent and very important. This deserves your time

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:23.880
and attention, right? This is where you will focus because it is both important enough

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:29.959
to merit that, but also urgent enough that you need to do it. Now, task two is very urgent.

00:08:29.959 --> 00:08:32.960
Not all that important in the Eisenhower matrix. This is something you're going to delegate,

00:08:32.960 --> 00:08:35.880
right? This is something you're going to hand off to somebody else because it might not

00:08:35.880 --> 00:08:39.799
be important enough to merit your direct attention, but it's urgent. It needs to get done. So

00:08:39.799 --> 00:08:45.799
we will delegate it. Task three, not urgent or important. Bye-bye. Simple answer for this

00:08:45.799 --> 00:08:48.919
one in the Eisenhower matrix is that we cut it from our task list, right? This does not

00:08:48.919 --> 00:08:54.799
get anybody's attention. And task four, this is something that is important, but not super

00:08:54.799 --> 00:08:59.099
urgent. You're going to schedule this. So this gets built into your long-term plans.

00:08:59.099 --> 00:09:03.880
You build out work plans for it. You put it on your calendar. You make sure this happens

00:09:03.880 --> 00:09:08.479
because it's important, but it doesn't have to happen this moment. So you're scheduling

00:09:08.479 --> 00:09:12.960
it. So I came across this, and I thought, you know, this is really good. This is really

00:09:12.960 --> 00:09:16.840
going to help me. And I tried to implement it. I went through a few rounds of sort of

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:21.799
trying to use this tool, and I kept tweaking it and adapting it until I felt like I'd gotten

00:09:21.799 --> 00:09:25.640
to something different, right? So I went from calling it the Eisenhower matrix to calling

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:30.840
it the Gonzales matrix. I named it for my boss, and I promise you she is thrilled with

00:09:30.840 --> 00:09:37.559
this honor. But like I said, I tweaked it. I adapted it enough that I felt like it was

00:09:37.559 --> 00:09:41.760
a little bit different. And so in this case, rather than urgency and importance, I'm focusing

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:46.760
on effort and value, right? How effortful is something and how valuable is it? And rather

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:51.039
than tasks, I'm thinking about projects, right? We've moved from the task level to the project

00:09:51.039 --> 00:09:55.000
level because that's what made most sense for my team. That's kind of how we work, and

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:01.239
it made sense to keep and cut at the project level. So here, high value, low effort project.

00:10:01.239 --> 00:10:05.320
This is great. This is where we focus. This is where we want our attention. And as many

00:10:05.320 --> 00:10:08.520
of these as we can get is really what we want, because we're producing a whole lot

00:10:08.520 --> 00:10:12.919
of value without putting in a whole lot of work. Project two is the one that we're scheduling

00:10:12.919 --> 00:10:18.119
in this version of this. Very effortful, but also very valuable, so worth it. Because it's

00:10:18.119 --> 00:10:22.080
more effortful, it's probably going to require iterations and collaboration, right? So you're

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:25.599
building this into work plans, and you're really sort of establishing how this is going

00:10:25.599 --> 00:10:32.119
to go long term. Project three, high effort, low value, buh-bye. We don't want anything

00:10:32.119 --> 00:10:36.520
to do with project three, because it does not merit that level of effort. And project

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:39.919
four is the one that we would maybe delegate, right? We think about handing this off to

00:10:39.919 --> 00:10:45.760
a junior member of the team, perhaps, because it's not so valuable that if it doesn't go

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:49.400
well, it's going to really hurt the team. But it's also not so effortful that it's going

00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:54.559
to interfere with more important things, right? So this is a good learning ground for somebody

00:10:54.559 --> 00:10:58.520
who's coming up through the ranks, and so it could be one that you would delegate to

00:10:58.520 --> 00:11:04.080
them. So at this point, I want to acknowledge something, which is that this is a pretty

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:09.799
simple idea. This is a cost-benefit analysis set on a grid, right? There's nothing groundbreaking

00:11:09.799 --> 00:11:17.320
here. It's useful, and I will encourage you to use it or something like it, but I don't

00:11:17.320 --> 00:11:21.479
want to pretend like I have invented the wheel here, because I have not. This is a simple

00:11:21.479 --> 00:11:27.320
idea. So what's the point? Why am I telling you this? I think the really useful piece

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:35.320
of this is that it is a hand chair. It is a hand chair because, to me, a hand chair

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:40.239
is the definitive example of a conversation piece, right? I can't imagine walking into

00:11:40.239 --> 00:11:45.960
someone's home and seeing one of those and not having a conversation about it. And that's

00:11:45.960 --> 00:11:50.599
what I want you to think of when you see the Gonzales Matrix, right, is all of the questions

00:11:50.599 --> 00:11:53.919
that pop into my mind when you see a hand chair, when I see a hand chair, I want you

00:11:53.919 --> 00:11:57.719
to have all of those questions, for all of that to come up when you think about your

00:11:57.719 --> 00:12:03.919
projects or your tasks laid out on a matrix, and then to have that conversation in a structured

00:12:03.919 --> 00:12:08.359
and productive and helpful way. So that's really what I'm trying to give you here, is

00:12:08.359 --> 00:12:12.479
the permission and encouragement and structure in which you can have a conversation that

00:12:12.479 --> 00:12:19.000
will be helpful for you and for your team, okay? Hand chairs. Does anybody have a hand

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:26.799
chair? Really, I have questions. Please come find me if you do. So I've been talking about

00:12:26.799 --> 00:12:29.719
a conversation, right? It's a conversation piece. That's how I want you to think about

00:12:29.719 --> 00:12:35.719
this. And that's true, but I want to acknowledge that some people use the word conversation

00:12:35.719 --> 00:12:41.919
as a euphemism for conflict, right? That happens. I'm a family therapist by training. I've seen

00:12:41.919 --> 00:12:46.840
that happen. So I want to acknowledge that conversations are not necessarily always easy

00:12:46.840 --> 00:12:52.719
or perfect. This is actually meant to prevent conflict in that we're trying to make explicit

00:12:52.719 --> 00:12:57.840
things that are implicit and lead to conflict. But again, I know it's not perfectly easy

00:12:57.840 --> 00:13:02.840
to do so, and so I want to acknowledge that. And so here I'm going to give you some guidelines

00:13:02.840 --> 00:13:08.440
and set some expectations for what I think you can expect to see as you go through this.

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:13.400
First, how should you talk about effort and value, right? What is the right way to have

00:13:13.400 --> 00:13:17.520
this conversation? At a very high level, I would say you want to be systematic, you

00:13:17.520 --> 00:13:21.960
want to be transparent, and you want to be open-minded. Systematic in that this is an

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:25.239
iterative exercise. You're going to come back to this time and time again every time a new

00:13:25.239 --> 00:13:29.880
project pops up, maybe, or on some regular schedule. And you want to do it the same way

00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:33.840
as you go through it each time, because that consistency will allow the people on your

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:38.320
team to have that sort of mental model, right? That prediction about how this is going to

00:13:38.320 --> 00:13:42.880
go each time, and to get better at guessing how projects are going to be rated on effort

00:13:42.880 --> 00:13:48.760
and value. So that's important to be systematic in that way. Transparently also, because

00:13:48.760 --> 00:13:54.840
if we are driven by some internal bias, something that we're not acknowledging in our rating

00:13:54.840 --> 00:13:58.520
of effort and value, that's going to be clear to people. They're going to know that something

00:13:58.520 --> 00:14:02.080
is off between what you're saying, what you're describing about a particular project, and

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:07.320
how you're rating it. And that gap that people are going to feel is going to quash the conversation,

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:12.320
which is the opposite of what we want. And so you need to be transparent about, you know,

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:16.000
I don't like working with project team X, so I'm going to rate this as not very valuable

