to be prepared to let people know if your decision is the final one, that needs to be

00:17:14.859 --> 00:17:18.420
clear going into this. If this is a democratic process in which everybody's vote counts the

00:17:18.420 --> 00:17:22.760
same, that needs to be clear, too. So there's not a right or wrong way to do it, but acknowledging

00:17:22.760 --> 00:17:27.380
that these differences are going to play out in one of a few ways is important to do ahead

00:17:27.380 --> 00:17:28.380
of time.

00:17:29.140 --> 00:17:33.260
And then finally, the need for flexibility. People might want things that do not necessarily

00:17:33.260 --> 00:17:38.619
align with this, with this matrix, with this grid, and so being ready, if you have the

00:17:38.619 --> 00:17:43.420
flexibility to exercise it, to say, okay, we can spend time on this because you really

00:17:43.420 --> 00:17:48.540
want to, and that is okay, even though it doesn't line up necessarily with our ratings.

00:17:48.540 --> 00:17:52.060
Or if you can't, acknowledging that ahead of time, saying, no, we are too strapped,

00:17:52.060 --> 00:17:57.540
we need to focus in exactly the way that is prescribed. So being ready for that.

00:17:57.540 --> 00:18:02.140
Finally, why? I know this is a little late for this in the talk, but I'd say how does

00:18:02.140 --> 00:18:07.420
this help? It helps in a few ways. One is it limits this everything is critical mindset,

00:18:07.420 --> 00:18:11.500
right? Everything might be critical, but not everything can be equally critical, and that's

00:18:11.500 --> 00:18:15.699
really what this exercise is about. This is really be how you say no to your boss, right?

00:18:15.699 --> 00:18:20.939
You ask them for help prioritizing so that you can focus. It also is going to get everybody

00:18:20.939 --> 00:18:25.739
rowing in the same direction, as they say. If you can align your team's perspective and

00:18:25.739 --> 00:18:30.060
clarify responsibilities, get everybody to think the same way about what's valuable,

00:18:30.060 --> 00:18:34.099
you will really, really produce a whole lot more than if you were all kind of spinning

00:18:34.099 --> 00:18:37.979
wheels independently and maybe even going different directions. So that is a really

00:18:37.979 --> 00:18:42.300
important benefit, and it's part of why doing less can actually make you more productive

00:18:42.300 --> 00:18:48.579
in addition to just feeling better. And then finally, this is a really good training ground

00:18:48.579 --> 00:18:54.060
for teaching junior folks to communicate and to, you know, be willing to voice their

00:18:54.060 --> 00:18:58.780
perspective on this stuff. We want our junior folks to get that kind of training, and as

00:18:58.780 --> 00:19:04.660
Andrew so beautifully spoke about, it is, you know, not born in any of us, so we need

00:19:04.660 --> 00:19:10.900
to give them the space to learn that, and this exercise is a great way to do that.

00:19:10.900 --> 00:19:14.540
Wrapping up with a quick summary, here's what I am proposing to you, basically, is that

00:19:14.660 --> 00:19:19.339
you get that flood of messages in your inbox and you feel overwhelmed. I think it's actually

00:19:19.339 --> 00:19:23.180
a little bit different. I think there's a cognitive path here that goes from flood of

00:19:23.180 --> 00:19:30.579
messages to FOMO to too many projects to feeling overwhelmed, and that by recognizing the FOMO,

00:19:30.579 --> 00:19:35.900
putting it in its place with the Gonzales matrix, and then culling projects and feeling

00:19:35.900 --> 00:19:42.619
better gets you actually from flood of messages more directly to this feeling of serenity

00:19:42.619 --> 00:19:45.260
now and productivity later. Thank you.

